The **editables.min.js** library is a lightweight JavaScript solution designed for dynamic content editing on web applications.

It offers two main features:

1. **single-editable fields**, which allow developers to toggle between read-only and editable modes for individual elements with ease; and

2. **multiple-editable fields**, which provide a structured way to edit data in tables using contenteditable cells.

Both features include seamless event handling for saving or canceling changes, ensuring a smooth user experience. The library is highly customizable, enabling developers to integrate editable functionality with minimal effort.

Ideal for real-time data updates, it simplifies content management workflows.

---

The **multiple-editable-fields** library enables the creation of editable tables with dynamic cells. It simplifies handling user input by using `contenteditable` elements and event listeners to update table data in real-time.

####1. Draw a Table with Attributes

Define an HTML table with `td` elements that include the attributes `data-label`, `data-id`, `data-field`, and the `contenteditable` attribute. Here's an example:

```html
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Name</th>
      <th>Time Zone</th>
      <th>Job Title</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td data-label=\"Name\" data-id=\"1\" data-field=\"name\" contenteditable>John Doe</td>
      <td data-label=\"Time Zone\" data-id=\"1\" data-field=\"timezone\" contenteditable>UTC-5</td>
      <td data-label=\"Job Title\" data-id=\"1\" data-field=\"job\" contenteditable>Software Engineer</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
```

####2. Initialize Editable `td` Elements

Use the `init_contenteditable` function to initialize the `contenteditable` elements. Provide a callback to handle the updated data when the user presses Enter:

```javascript
init_contenteditable(function(id, field, value) {
    console.log(`ID: ${id}, Field: ${field}, New Value: ${value}`);
    alert('Value updated!');
});
```

This function binds event listeners to the table cells for smooth interaction and updates.




